<Input><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,255]">Which we can see is equivalent to the zero matrix of equal dimension, and that the substitution into the characteristic polynomial is equivalent.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">iii) Assuming that <Font bold="true">A</Font> is invertible, find the inverse of <Font bold="true">A</Font> using the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem. (Hint: rewrite the equation and multiply it by <Font bold="true">A</Font>^-1), doing the final calculation in Maple.</Font><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,255]"> </Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,255]">Firstly, we need to work out the inverse using the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem:</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal" alignment="centred"><Equation executable="true" style="2D Math" input-equation="" display=""></Equation></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
